<DIV class=3Dbody>
<DIV class=3Ddiv1>
<H2><A id=3Dheading0 shape=3Drect name=3Dheading0><SPAN =
class=3Dlln>0</SPAN>=20
Introduction</A></H2>
<DIV class=3Ddiv2>
<H3><A id=3Dsubheading0_1 shape=3Drect name=3Dsubheading0_1><SPAN =
class=3Dlln>0.1</SPAN>=20
Purpose of This Document</A></H3>
<P>Writing systems are main part of cultures, together with languages =
and=20
scripts. Each cultural community has its own language, script and =
writing=20
system. In that sense, the transfer of each writing system into cyber =
space is a=20
task with very important responsibility for information and =
communication=20
technology. </P>
<P>As one of the basic work items of this task, this document describes =
issues=20
of text layout in the Japanese writing system. The goal of this task is =
not to=20
propose solutions itself but describe important issues as the basic =
information=20
for actual implementations. </P></DIV><!--div2-->
<DIV class=3Ddiv2>
<H3><A id=3Dsubheading0_2 shape=3Drect name=3Dsubheading0_2><SPAN =
class=3Dlln>0.2</SPAN>=20
How This Document Was Created</A></H3>
<P>This document was created by the W3C Japanese Layout Task Force. This =
Task=20
Force is organized with the following members, and has discussed a lot =
of issues=20
to harmonize the requirements from user communities and solutions from=20
technological experts. </P>
<OL>
  <LI>
  <P>Experts of Japanese Text Layout (The editors of "JIS X =
4051:Formatting=20
  rules for Japanese documents")</P>
  <LI>
  <P>Experts of internationalization and standardization in Japan (from=20
  Microsoft, Antenna House, Justsystems)</P>
  <LI>
  <P>Other members of the W3C <A href=3D"http://www.w3.org/Style/CSS/"=20
  shape=3Drect>CSS</A>, <A =
href=3D"http://www.w3.org/International/core/"=20
  shape=3Drect>i18n Core</A>, <A =
href=3D"http://www.w3.org/Graphics/SVG/"=20
  shape=3Drect>SVG</A> and <A href=3D"http://www.w3.org/Style/XSL/"=20
  shape=3Drect>XSL</A> Working Groups. </P></LI></OL>
<P>This task force is also an outstanding effort as a bilingual =
methodology.=20
Discussion is mainly conducted in Japanese, because of the Japanese =
issues, but,=20
minutes and mailing list are written in English. As a process of the=20
development, the task force held already one face-to-face meeting with =
the=20
participating Working Groups. </P>
<P>This document itself was also developed bilingually, and is published =

bilingually. As for technical terms, we carefully avoided to use jargon. =
Even if=20
there are some English words corresponding to the Japanese words, we =
carefully=20
studied the differences of the actual meaning, and if there are some =
differences=20
between corresponding concepts, we decided to provide the Japanese =
jargon in=20
ROMAJI (Latin transliteration) for future discussion. Moreover, we =
prepared as=20
many figures as possible with clear and understandable English for non =
Japanese=20
readers. </P></DIV><!--div2-->
<DIV class=3Ddiv2>
<H3><A id=3Dsubheading0_3 shape=3Drect name=3Dsubheading0_3><SPAN =
class=3Dlln>0.3</SPAN>=20
Basic Principle of Development of this Document</A></H3>
<P>Japanese Text Layout has several differences from Latin script based =
Text=20
Layout. Major differences include:</P>
<OL>
  <LI>
  <P>In Japanese Text Layout, not only horizontal composition but also =
vertical=20
  composition is used.</P>
  <LI>
  <P>The width of all KANJI and KANA characters are mostly full width, =
and there=20
  are no spaces between these characters.</P></LI></OL>
<P>Accordingly, this document mainly explains the characteristics of =
Japanese=20
Text Layout using the following policy.</P>
<OL>
  <LI>
  <P>It does not fully cover all issues of the Japanese text layout =
system, but=20
  mainly discusses the differences from Western text layout systems. =
</P>
  <LI>
  <P>It focuses on requirements to be established as Japanese text =
layout=20
  presentation form. Technology-specific interpretations of the =
requirements=20
  and/or how to implement them are out of scope of this document. </P>
  <LI>
  <P>It explicitly refers to JIS X 4051 "Formatting rules for Japanese=20
  documents" as much as possible. Also, unless an issue is not explained =
in JIS=20
  X 4051, this document is focused on basic issues of Japanese layout.=20
  Accordingly, some issues have only reference to the corresponding =
clause of=20
  JIS X 4051. To implement a high quality Japanese text layout system, =
the=20
  implementers have to refer to JIS X 4051, however, the description of =
this=20
  document is sufficient to recognize the basic characteristics of =
Japanese text=20
  layout as basic knowledge. Also, some issues, which are not described =
in JIS X=20
  4051, are described in detail. </P>
  <P>With this policy, this document includes tutorial- or summary-like, =

  supplemental explanation, related background, and additional =
description of=20
  JIS X 4051. This document covers all basic issues of Japanese text =
layout, but=20
  JIS X 4051 has to be referred to for advanced discussion. </P>
  <LI>
  <P>It provides typical examples in actual use for key text layout =
features for=20
  better understanding of their usage.</P>
  <LI>
  <P>For non Japanese readers, frequency of usage for each issue is =
indicated.=20
  These frequencies are not the outcome from any accurate research, but =
from the=20
  long experience of the authors. These frequencies are easy to imagine =
for=20
  ordinary Japanese text readers, however, it may be difficult to =
imagine=20
  without explicit information for non Japanese readers. These =
frequencies are=20
  only rough information to prioritize the importance of issues. An =
example:=20
</P>
  <P>"WARICHU is not frequently used, but is useful to simply annotate =
persons,=20
  things, and so on, on the appeared place, especially in classics or=20
  translations." "RUBY is frequently used in modern documents including=20
  newspapers." </P>
  <LI>
  <P>Considering non Japanese readers of this document, figures are used =
for=20
  explanation as much as possible.</P>
  <LI>
  <P>Text layout rules and recommendations for readable design are =
different=20
  topics. However, these two issues are difficult to discuss separately. =
In this=20
  document, these two aspects are carefully separated. The aesthetic =
design=20
  recommendations are mainly described as notes. </P>
  <LI>
  <P>The main target of this document is common books. The authors' =
experiences=20
  are mainly common books, and the required quality of common books is =
the=20
  highest in the market. There are many kinds of books in the market, =
and the=20
  requirements are quite diversified. The task force has a lot of =
accumulated=20
  experiences in requirements and solutions to Japanese layout. Also, =
the=20
  issues, which have been discussed for a long time, are applicable for =
other=20
  kinds of publication. </P>
  <P>In terms of frequency, the importance of magazine, manual, Web =
document=20
  have no difference from common books. Also there are several =
characteristics=20
  in these publications which are different from common books. These =
issues=20
  should be treated in future documents. </P></LI></OL></DIV><!--div2-->
<DIV class=3Ddiv2>
<H3><A id=3Dsubheading0_4 shape=3Drect name=3Dsubheading0_4><SPAN =
class=3Dlln>0.4</SPAN>=20
The Structure of This Document</A></H3>
<P>This document consists of three parts:</P>
<DL>
  <DD>
  <P>1 The basic specification of Japanese text layout</P>
  <DD>
  <P>2 The processing of line layout</P>
  <DD>
  <P>3 The method of HANMEN design</P></DD></DL>
<P>Section 1 explains the characteristics of letters and symbols, which =
are used=20
in Japanese text layout, their differences in vertical layout and =
horizontal=20
layout, and the design and adaptation of KIHONHANMEN. </P>
<P>Section 2 explains line layout methods for KANJI, KANA, YAKUMONO, =
together=20
with RUBY (inter line pronunciation and annotation) and mixture of =
Western=20
letters.</P>
<P>Section 3 describes the construction method and layout method of =
headings,=20
notes, illustrations and tables.</P>
<P>In principle, characters in Japanese layout are full-width, =
mono-spaced and=20
positioned without spaces (solid setting). This is taken as a premise =
for the=20
design of KIHONHANMEN, the basis of book layout. Furthermore, following =
the=20
design of KIHONHANMEN, figures, characters, symbols etc. are placed in =
an actual=20
page. For the understanding of Japanese layout it is an important aspect =
to=20
understand the design of the KIHONHANMEN and how to position figures,=20
characters, symbols etc. following KIHONHANMEN. Hence, section 1 =
describes the=20
design of KIHONHANMEN and its application methods in detail. Especially =
section=20
1.5 "Pagewise Arrangements of KIHONHANMEN Elements" provides =
prototypical=20
patterns about the following three guidelines, what is strictly =
recommended to=20
be taken into account, and what exceptions are possible. The goal of =
this=20
explanation is the understanding of Japanese layout. Since detailed =
explanations=20
of the various elements of "KIHONHANMEN" are given in section 2 and 3, =
some=20
explanations are being repeated. </P>
<OL>
  <LI>
  <P>Keep the basic size or column numbers, which is decided in =
KIHONHANMEN.</P>
  <LI>
  <P>Keep the line positions, which are decided in KIHONHANMEN, with =
some=20
  exceptions.</P>
  <LI>
  <P>Keep the letter positions, which are decided in KIHONHANMEN, with =
some=20
  exceptions.</P></LI></OL></DIV><!--div2-->
<DIV class=3Ddiv2>
<H3><A id=3Dsubheading0_5 shape=3Drect name=3Dsubheading0_5><SPAN =
class=3Dlln>0.5</SPAN>=20
Reference of Definition and Others</A></H3>
<P>The definitions of technical terms are described in a separate =
document. The=20
notation of technical terms and reference to the definitions are as =
follows:=20
</P>
<P>TBD</P></DIV><!--div2--></DIV>
<DIV class=3Ddiv1>
<H2><A id=3Dheading1 shape=3Drect name=3Dheading1><SPAN =
class=3Dlln>1</SPAN> Basics of=20
Japanese Text Layout</A></H2>
<DIV class=3Ddiv2>
<H3><A id=3Dsubheading1_1 shape=3Drect name=3Dsubheading1_1><SPAN =
class=3Dlln>1.1</SPAN>=20
Page Formats for Japanese Documents</A></H3>
<DIV class=3Ddiv3>
<H4><A id=3Dsubheading1_1_1 shape=3Drect name=3Dsubheading1_1_1><SPAN=20
class=3Dlln>1.1.1</SPAN> Specification of Page Formats</A></H4>
<P class=3Dbody>Page formats of a Japanese document shall be specified =
by:</P>
<UL>
  <LI>
  <P>Firstly, preparing the page templates which determine the basic =
appearance=20
  of pages of the document;</P>
  <LI>
  <P>Then, specifying the details of actual Page elements based on the=20
  templates.</P></LI></UL></DIV><!--div3-->
<DIV class=3Ddiv3>
<H4><A id=3Dsubheading1_1_2 shape=3Drect name=3Dsubheading1_1_2><SPAN=20
class=3Dlln>1.1.2</SPAN> Page Formats and Page Templates</A></H4>
<P class=3Dbody>Generally, books use only one page template and =
magazines often=20
use several templates.</P></DIV><!--div3-->
<P>As said before, although in books there is one pattern of page =
design, the=20
basic pattern is adapted for e.g. the table of contents. Furthermore, =
there are=20
many examples of indices which have a different layout than the basic =
layout.=20
And, in books in vertical setting, often indices are in horizontal =
setting. It=20
holds also for such cases where the goal is to make the size of HANMEN =
for=20
indices close to the size of HANMEN in the basic design. </P>
<P>Magazines gather articles of different kinds. Often the layout will =
differ=20
depending on the content of the article, like one part with 9 point =
character=20
size and 3 columns, and another part with 8 point character size and 4 =
columns.=20
</P>
<DIV class=3Ddiv3>
<H4><A id=3Dsubheading1_1_3 shape=3Drect name=3Dsubheading1_1_3><SPAN=20
class=3Dlln>1.1.3</SPAN> Elements of Page Templates</A></H4>
<P class=3Dbody>The following are the basic elements of page template =
(<SPAN=20
class=3Dfigure_ref>Figure 1-1</SPAN> illustrates an example of a page =
template=20
with Vertical composition). </P>
<DIV class=3Dfigure><IMG=20
alt=3D"Figure 1-1 An Example of a Page Template for Vertical =
Composition"=20
src=3D"http://www.w3.org/TR/jlreq/Images/img1_1.png">=20
<DIV class=3DfigureTitle><SPAN class=3Dlln>Figure 1-1</SPAN> An Example =
of a Page=20
Template for Vertical Composition </DIV></DIV><!--figure-->
<OL>
  <LI>
  <P>Trim size and binding side (Japanese documents with vertical =
composition=20
  are bound on the right-hand side, and documents with horizontal =
composition=20
  are bound on the left-hand side. See <SPAN =
class=3Dfigure_ref>Fig.1-2</SPAN>. )=20
  </P>
  <LI>
  <P>Principal Text direction (vertical composition or horizontal=20
  composition)</P>
  <LI>
  <P>The appearance of KIHONHANMEN and its position relative to the trim =

size</P>
  <LI>
  <P>The appearance of Running Heads and Folios and their positions =
relative to=20
  the trim size and KIHONHANMEN</P></LI></OL>
<DIV class=3Dfigure><IMG=20
alt=3D"Figure 1-2 Binding-Side (Left-Hand Side Binding and Right-Hand =
Side Binding)"=20
src=3D"http://www.w3.org/TR/jlreq/Images/img1_2.png">=20
<DIV class=3DfigureTitle><SPAN class=3Dlln>Figure 1-2</SPAN> =
Binding-side (left-hand=20
side binding and right-hand side binding) =
</DIV></DIV><!--figure--></DIV><!--div3-->
<DIV class=3Ddiv3>
<H4><A id=3Dsubheading1_1_4 shape=3Drect name=3Dsubheading1_1_4><SPAN=20
class=3Dlln>1.1.4</SPAN> Elements of KIHONHANMEN</A></H4>
<P class=3Dbody>KIHONHANMEN is the HANMEN style designed as the basis of =
a book.=20
The following are the basic elements of KIHONHANMEN (See <SPAN=20
class=3Dfigure_ref>Fig. 1-3</SPAN>). </P>
<TABLE class=3Dt_note>
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD class=3Dft>
      <P>(note 1)</P></TD>
    <TD>
      <P class=3Dft>The question of how the various elements of =
KIHONHANMEN are=20
      applied to a real page is an important aspect for the =
understanding of the=20
      characteristics of Japanese type setting. Accordingly, the details =
of=20
      KIHONHANMEN will be explained later. </P></TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD class=3Dft>
      <P>(note 2)</P></TD>
    <TD>
      <P class=3Dft>The normative definition of KIHONHANMEN is provided =
in JIS X=20
      4051, sec. 7.5.</P></TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD class=3Dft>
      <P>(note 3)</P></TD>
    <TD>
      <P class=3Dft>Design (including running head and folios) and type =
setting=20
      examples for KIHONHANMEN in different paper sizes are available in =
JIS X=20
      4051, annex 3 and 4. </P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE><!--t_note-->
<DIV class=3Dfigure><IMG=20
alt=3D"Figure 1-3 Elements of KIHONHANMEN (Example in Vertical =
Composition)"=20
src=3D"http://www.w3.org/TR/jlreq/Images/img1_3.png">=20
<DIV class=3DfigureTitle><SPAN class=3Dlln>Figure 1-3</SPAN> Elements of =
KIHONHANMEN=20
(Example in vertical composition) </DIV></DIV><!--figure-->
<OL>
  <LI>
  <P>Character size and Typeface name</P>
  <LI>
  <P>Text direction (vertical composition or horizontal composition)</P>
  <LI>
  <P>Number of columns and Column space when using multi-column =
formats</P>
  <LI>
  <P>Number of characters per line</P>
  <LI>
  <P>Number of lines per page (number of lines per column when using=20
  multi-column formats)</P>
  <LI>
  <P>line-gap (or Line feed)</P></LI></OL></DIV><!--div3-->
<DIV class=3Ddiv3>
<H3><A id=3Dsubheading1_1_5 shape=3Drect name=3Dsubheading1_1_5>1.1.5 =
KIHONHANMEN and=20
Examples of Real Page Design</A></H3>
<P>Below are several examples of how the basic style is created, and how =
then=20
various elements are placed on a real text page (This and other aspects =
of how=20
the various elements of KIHONHANMEN are arranged on each page are =
explained in=20
<A href=3D"http://www.w3.org/TR/jlreq/#subheading1_5" shape=3Drect>sec. =
1.5 Pagewise=20
Arrangements of KIHONHANMEN Elements</A>.). </P>
<OL>
  <LI>
  <P>Space and position of headings</P>
  <P>The space of line feed direction of headings is specified by using =
the line=20
  positions provided by KIHONHANMEN as a basis and by deciding how many =
times=20
  they need to be used. (Details of this processing are defined in JIS X =
4051,=20
  sec. 8.3.3. d). The Indentation of the text direction of the heading =
is=20
  normally specified by using the character position designed via =
KIHONHANMEN as=20
  a basis. The indentation is then several times of that position. In =
the=20
  example in <SPAN class=3Dfigure_ref>Figure A1-1</SPAN>, the heading is =
placed in=20
  the middle line of three lines which are provided via KIHONHANMEN. It =
is=20
  indented 4 characters of the character size provided via KIHONHANMEN. =
</P>
  <DIV class=3Dfigure><IMG=20
  alt=3D"Figure A1-1 Layout example of a heading based on the line =
position which is designed via KIHONHANMEN"=20
  src=3D"http://www.w3.org/TR/jlreq/Images/img_ad1_1.png">=20
  <DIV class=3DfigureTitle><SPAN>Figure A1-1</SPAN>=E3=80=80Layout =
example of a heading=20
  based on the line position which is designed via KIHONHANMEN =
</DIV></DIV><!--figure-->
  <TABLE class=3Dt_note>
    <TBODY>
    <TR>
      <TD class=3Dft>
        <P>(note 1)</P></TD>
      <TD>
        <P class=3Dft>Details of the different types of headings, =
creation of=20
        headings, methods for placing headings etc. are explained in =
sec. 3.1=20
        "Processing of Headings". =
</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE><!--t_note-->
  <LI>
  <P>Size of illustrations</P>
  <P>In horizontal setting with two columns, if at all possible, the =
width of=20
  illustrations should be either the width of one column (which is =
provided via=20
  KIHONHANMEN) or the width of KIHONHANMEN (see <SPAN =
class=3Dfigure_ref>Fig.=20
  A1-2</SPAN>). The position of illustrations is often the head or the =
Foot of=20
  the page (see <SPAN class=3Dfigure_ref>Fig. A1-2</SPAN>). </P>
  <DIV class=3Dfigure><IMG=20
  alt=3D"Figure A1-2 Example of illustrations in two columns, horizontal =
setting"=20
  src=3D"http://www.w3.org/TR/jlreq/Images/img_ad1_2.png">=20
  <DIV class=3DfigureTitle><SPAN>Figure A1-2</SPAN> Example of =
illustrations in=20
  two columns, horizontal setting </DIV></DIV><!--figure-->
  <TABLE class=3Dt_note>
    <TBODY>
    <TR>
      <TD class=3Dft>
        <P>(note 1)</P></TD>
      <TD>
        <P class=3Dft>Details of illustration positioning are explained =
in "sec.=20
        3.3 Positioning of Figures, Photographs =
etc.".</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE><!--t_note-->
  <LI>
  <P>HANMEN size for the Table of contents</P>
  <P>The HANMEN size for the table of contents of books is based on the =
size of=20
  KIHONHANMEN. There are many examples, for the table of contents in =
vertical=20
  layout, in which the size of the left-to-right line feed is identical =
to the=20
  size of KIHONHANMEN, and the text direction size for head and foot is =
a little=20
  bit smaller (see <SPAN class=3Dfigure_ref>Fig. A1-3</SPAN>). </P>
  <DIV class=3Dfigure><IMG=20
  alt=3D"Figure 1-3 Design example for the table of contents in vertical =
layout"=20
  src=3D"http://www.w3.org/TR/jlreq/Images/img_ad1_3.png">=20
  <DIV class=3DfigureTitle><SPAN>Figure 1-3</SPAN> Design example for =
the table of=20
  contents in vertical layout </DIV></DIV><!--figure-->
  <TABLE class=3Dt_note>
    <TBODY>
    <TR>
      <TD class=3Dft>
        <P>(note 1)</P></TD>
      <TD>
        <P class=3Dft>There are cases when a different HANMEN than =
KIHONHANMEN is=20
        used for positioning of running heads and folios. This will be =
discussed=20
        in "sec. 1.6.2 Principles of positioning running head and =
folios" (see=20
        <SPAN class=3Dfigure_ref>Fig. A1-17</SPAN>). =
</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE><!--t_note--></LI></OL></DIV><!--div3--></D=
IV><!--div2-->
<DIV class=3Ddiv2>
<H3><A id=3Dsubheading1_2 shape=3Drect name=3Dsubheading1_2><SPAN =
class=3Dlln>1.2</SPAN>=20
Japanese Characters - Dimensions of KANJI and KANA Characters</A></H3>
<DIV class=3Ddiv3>
<H4><A id=3Dsubheading1_2_1 shape=3Drect name=3Dsubheading1_2_1><SPAN=20
class=3Dlln>1.2.1</SPAN> Characters Used for Japanese Documents</A></H4>
<P class=3Dbody>Japanese characters used for composing Japanese text =
mainly=20
consist of KANJI and KANA (HIRAGANA and KATAKANA) (See <SPAN=20
class=3Dfigure_ref>Fig. 1-4</SPAN>). </P>
<DIV class=3Dfigure><IMG alt=3D"Figure 1-4 KANJI, HIRAGANA and KATAKANA" =

src=3D"http://www.w3.org/TR/jlreq/Images/img1_4.png">=20
<DIV class=3DfigureTitle><SPAN class=3Dlln>Figure 1-4</SPAN> KANJI, =
HIRAGANA and=20
KATAKANA </DIV></DIV><!--figure-->
<TABLE class=3Dt_note>
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD class=3Dft>
      <P>(note 1)</P></TD>
    <TD>
      <P class=3Dft>In addition to KANJI and KANA, various punctuation =
marks (See=20
      <SPAN class=3Dfigure_ref>Fig. 1-5</SPAN>) as well as Arabic =
numerals, Latin=20
      characters and/or Greek characters may be used in Japanese text. =
</P>
      <DIV class=3Dfigure><IMG alt=3D"Figure 1-5 Examples of punctuation =
marks"=20
      src=3D"http://www.w3.org/TR/jlreq/Images/img1_5.png">=20
      <DIV class=3DfigureTitle><SPAN class=3Dlln>Figure 1-5</SPAN> =
Examples of=20
      punctuation marks </DIV></DIV><!--figure--></TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD class=3Dft>
      <P>(note 2)</P></TD>
    <TD>
      <P class=3Dft>The details of characters and character classes used =
in this=20
      document will be explained in a separate document about =
terminology of=20
      Japanese Layout. Also, the relation of the characters and symbols =
from=20
      each character class to Unicode code points will be shown in an =
appendix=20
      to this document. =
</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE><!--t_note--></DIV><!--div3-->
<DIV class=3Ddiv3>
<H4><A id=3Dsubheading1_2_2 shape=3Drect name=3Dsubheading1_2_2><SPAN=20
class=3Dlln>1.2.2</SPAN> KANJI and KANA</A></H4>
<P class=3Dbody>KANJI and KANA characters that are of the same size have =
square=20
Imaginary bodies of equal dimensions (also known as the outer frame of a =

character). Aligned with the vertical and horizontal center of the =
imaginary=20
body, there is a smaller box called the Letter face which contains the =
actual=20
symbol. Character size shall be measured by the size of the imaginary =
body (See=20
<SPAN class=3Dfigure_ref>Fig. 1-6</SPAN>). "Character width" is a term =
to describe=20
the advance width of the imaginary body of a character in text direction =

(Direction of text advance). By definition it is equal to the "width" of =
a=20
character in horizontal composition, while it's the height of a =
character in=20
vertical composition (See <SPAN class=3Dfigure_ref>Fig. 1-6</SPAN>). =
</P>
<DIV class=3Dfigure><IMG=20
alt=3D"Figure 1-6 The Size of KANJI and KANA, and their imaginary =
bodies"=20
src=3D"http://www.w3.org/TR/jlreq/Images/img1_6.png">=20
<DIV class=3DfigureTitle><SPAN class=3Dlln>Figure 1-6</SPAN> The Size of =
KANJI and=20
KANA, and the imaginary bodies </DIV></DIV><!--figure-->
<TABLE class=3Dt_note>
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD class=3Dft>
      <P>(note 1)</P></TD>
    <TD>
      <P class=3Dft>The letter face of Small KANA (=E3=81=A3, =E3=82=87, =
=E3=83=A5, =E3=82=A1, =E3=82=A3, =E3=82=A5, etc) shall be=20
      placed at the vertical center and to the right of horizontal =
center of the=20
      imaginary body in vertical composition, and at the horizontal =
center and=20
      below the vertical center in horizontal composition. (See <SPAN=20
      class=3Dfigure_ref>Fig. 1-7</SPAN>). Also there are punctuation =
marks of=20
      which letter faces are not placed at the vertical and horizontal =
center of=20
      the imaginary body. </P>
      <DIV class=3Dfigure><IMG=20
      alt=3D"Figure 1-7 Small KANA letter and the position of its letter =
face in the imaginary body"=20
      src=3D"http://www.w3.org/TR/jlreq/Images/img1_7.png">=20
      <DIV class=3DfigureTitle><SPAN class=3Dlln>Figure 1-7</SPAN> Small =
KANA letter=20
      and the position of its letter face in the imaginary body =
</DIV></DIV><!--figure--></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE><!--t_note--></DIV><!-=
-div3-->
<DIV class=3Ddiv3>
<H4><A id=3Dsubheading1_2_3 shape=3Drect name=3Dsubheading1_2_3><SPAN=20
class=3Dlln>1.2.3</SPAN> Principles of Arrangement of KANJI and KANA=20
Characters</A></H4>
<P class=3Dbody>When composing a line with KANJI and KANA characters, in =
principle=20
no extra space between their imaginary bodies is placed. This is called =
Solid=20
setting (See <SPAN class=3Dfigure_ref>Fig. 1-8</SPAN>). </P>
<DIV class=3Dfigure><IMG=20
alt=3D"Figure 1-8 Example of solid setting in horizontal composition"=20
src=3D"http://www.w3.org/TR/jlreq/Images/img1_8.png">=20
<DIV class=3DfigureTitle><SPAN class=3Dlln>Figure 1-8</SPAN> Example of =
solid=20
setting in horizontal composition </DIV></DIV><!--figure-->
<TABLE class=3Dt_note>
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD class=3Dft>
      <P>(note 1)</P></TD>
    <TD>
      <P class=3Dft>Since the Letterpress printing era, KANJI and KANA =
letters=20
      have been designed so that they are easy to read regardless of =
text=20
      direction and with the solid setting. However, unlike the =
letterpress era=20
      when several sizes of the Original pattern of a letter was =
required to=20
      create Matrices, in today's digital era, because the same original =
pattern=20
      can be used for any size simply by enlargement or reduction,=20
      Inter-character spacing might be necessary when composing lines =
with large=20
      character size. </P></TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD class=3Dft>
      <P>(note 2)</P></TD>
    <TD>
      <P class=3Dft>Depending on the contents, there are several =
settings in=20
      addition to the solid setting as shown below.</P>
      <OL>
        <LI>
        <P>AKIGUMI (Fixed space setting): Text setting with a fixed size =
of=20
        Space between every two imaginary bodies (See <SPAN=20
        class=3Dfigure_ref>Fig. 1-9</SPAN>). </P>
        <DIV class=3Dfigure><IMG=20
        alt=3D"Figure 1-9 Examples of AKIGUMI in horizontal composition" =

        src=3D"http://www.w3.org/TR/jlreq/Images/img1_9.png">=20
        <DIV class=3DfigureTitle><SPAN class=3Dlln>Figure 1-9</SPAN> =
Examples of=20
        AKIGUMI in horizontal composition. </DIV></DIV><!--figure-->
        <P>AKIGUMI in books is used for the following reasons.</P>
        <OL>
          <LI>
          <P>To achieve a balance between running heads with a few and =
with many=20
          characters. AKIGUMI is used for the running heads with a few=20
          characters. Examples of AKIGUMI for running heads are given in =
JIS X=20
          4051, annex 5. </P>
          <LI>
          <P>To achieve a balance between headings with a few and with =
many=20
          characters. AKIGUMI is used for the headings with a few =
characters.=20
          Examples of AKIGUMI for headings are given in JIS X 4051, =
annex 6.=20
</P>
          <LI>
          <P>For captions of illustrations and tables which only have a =
few=20
          characters. AKIGUMI is used to get a balance to the size of=20
          illustration or table. </P>
          <LI>
          <P>In some cases, AKIGUMI is used for Chinese and Japanese =
poetry with=20
          one line which has only a few characters.</P></LI></OL>
        <TABLE class=3Dt_note>
          <TBODY>
          <TR>
            <TD class=3Dft>
              <P>(note 1)</P></TD>
            <TD>
              <P class=3Dft>AKIGUMI is defined in JIS X 4051, sec. =
4.18.1 b, which=20
              includes also =
Tracking.</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE><!--t_note-->
        <LI>
        <P>Equal inter-character space setting: Text setting with equal=20
        inter-character space per line so that each line is aligned on =
the same=20
        line head and line-end. (See <SPAN class=3Dfigure_ref>Fig. =
1-10</SPAN>).=20
        </P>
        <DIV class=3Dfigure><IMG=20
        alt=3D"Figure 1-10 Example of equal inter-character space =
setting in horizontal composition"=20
        src=3D"http://www.w3.org/TR/jlreq/Images/img1_10.png">=20
        <DIV class=3DfigureTitle><SPAN class=3Dlln>Figure 1-10</SPAN> =
Example of=20
        equal inter-character space setting in horizontal composition=20
        </DIV></DIV><!--figure-->
        <P>Equal inter-character space setting in books is used for =
unifying the=20
        length of table headings with Japanese text (see <SPAN=20
        class=3Dfigure_ref>Fig. A1-4</SPAN>). There are also examples =
(e.g. lists=20
        of names) in which parts of person names receive equal spacing. =
</P>
        <DIV class=3Dfigure><IMG=20
        alt=3D"Figure A1-4 Example of a table with equal spacing"=20
        src=3D"http://www.w3.org/TR/jlreq/Images/img_ad1_4.png">=20
        <DIV class=3DfigureTitle><SPAN>Figure A1-4</SPAN> Example of a =
table with=20
        equal spacing </DIV></DIV><!--figure-->
        <TABLE class=3Dt_note>
          <TBODY>
          <TR>
            <TD class=3Dft>
              <P>(note 1)</P></TD>
            <TD>
              <P class=3Dft>Equal spacing is defined in JIS X 4051, sec. =
4.18.1,=20
              including processing of =
JIDORI.</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE><!--t_note-->
        <LI>
        <P>TSUMEGUMI (kerning / tracking) : Text setting with reduced=20
        inter-character space by arranging characters so that a portion =
of two=20
        imaginary bodies are laid to overlap each other. This is divided =
further=20
        into two types depending on the methods of inter-character space =

        reduction. One method is to reduce the same amount of =
inter-character=20
        space (Tracking, See <SPAN class=3Dfigure_ref>Fig. 1-11</SPAN>) =
and the=20
        other is to determine the amount of space to reduce based on the =

        distance between two letter faces of adjacent characters (Letter =
face=20
        kerning, See <SPAN class=3Dfigure_ref>Fig. 1-12</SPAN>). </P>
        <DIV class=3Dfigure><IMG=20
        alt=3D"Figure 1-11 Example of tracking in horizonatl setting"=20
        src=3D"http://www.w3.org/TR/jlreq/Images/img1_11.png">=20
        <DIV class=3DfigureTitle><SPAN class=3Dlln>Figure 1-11</SPAN> =
Example of=20
        tracking (in horizontal composition, 2nd line. The 1st line is =
the same=20
        text with the solid setting for comparison) =
</DIV></DIV><!--figure-->
        <DIV class=3Dfigure><IMG=20
        alt=3D"Figure 1-12 Example of letter face kerning in horizontal =
composition"=20
        src=3D"http://www.w3.org/TR/jlreq/Images/img1_12.png">=20
        <DIV class=3DfigureTitle><SPAN class=3Dlln>Figure 1-12</SPAN> =
Example of=20
        letter face kerning (in horizontal composition, 2nd line. The =
1st line=20
        is the same text with the solid setting for comparison) =
</DIV></DIV><!--figure-->
        <P>There are examples in books where kerning and letter face =
kerning is=20
        used for e.g. headings with large size characters. In the main =
text, the=20
        most reader friendly approach is solid setting. However, if the=20
        character size is larger, it may happen the distance between =
characters=20
        becomes unbalanced, and kerning or letter face kerning will be =
applied.=20
        These methods are rarely used in books, for which easiness of =
reading is=20
        very important. But in magazines or advertisements there are =
examples of=20
        kerning and letter face kerning. Probably for magazines the =
structuring=20
        of pages is very important, and characters on a page need to be =
settled.=20
        =
</P></LI></OL></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE><!--t_note--></DIV><!--div3--></D=
IV><!--div2-->
<DIV class=3Ddiv2>
<H3><A id=3Dsubheading1_3 shape=3Drect name=3Dsubheading1_3><SPAN =
class=3Dlln>1.3</SPAN>=20
Directional Factors in Japanese Text Layout</A></H3>
<DIV class=3Ddiv3>
<H4><A id=3Dsubheading1_3_1 shape=3Drect name=3Dsubheading1_3_1><SPAN=20
class=3Dlln>1.3.1</SPAN> Vertical Composition and Horizontal =
Composition</A></H4>
<P class=3Dbody>Japanese text is laid out either in a vertical direction =
(vertical=20
writing) or in a horizontal direction (horizontal writing). Depending on =
the=20
content, either of the directions may be chosen. </P>
<TABLE class=3Dt_note>
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD class=3Dft>
      <P>(note 1)</P></TD>
    <TD>
      <P class=3Dft>KANJI and KANA characters for Japanese text layout =
have=20
      basically been designed to have the same dimensions of a square =
body, and=20
      the same collection of types can be used in either vertical =
composition or=20
      horizontal composition simply by changing the direction of text. =
(See=20
      <SPAN class=3Dfigure_ref>Fig. 1-13</SPAN>). There were some =
attempts to=20
      develop Printing types designed exclusively for horizontal =
composition,=20
      but they were not widely accepted. </P>
      <DIV class=3Dfigure><IMG=20
      alt=3D"Figure 1-13 Vertical composition and horizontal =
composition"=20
      src=3D"http://www.w3.org/TR/jlreq/Images/img1_13.png">=20
      <DIV class=3DfigureTitle><SPAN class=3Dlln>Figure 1-13</SPAN> =
Vertical=20
      composition and horizontal composition (The arrows show the =
reading=20
      direction) </DIV></DIV><!--figure--></TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD class=3Dft>
      <P>(note 2)</P></TD>
    <TD>
      <P class=3Dft>There is little market data comparing the number of =
pages with=20
      vertically and horizontally composed text, but it is said both are =
almost=20
      the same.</P></TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD class=3Dft>
      <P>(note 3)</P></TD>
    <TD>
      <P class=3Dft>For official (e.g. governmental) publications, =
horizontal=20
      setting is recommended, educational material (with the exception =
of=20
      certain topics) is mostly in horizontal setting, and furthermore, =
the=20
      readers of "mobile novels" are increasing, and it is expected that =
in the=20
      future, horizontal setting will increase in this area as well. =
However,=20
      most of the large newspapers are written completely in vertical =
setting,=20
      and most of the large journals for ordinary readers are almost =
completely=20
      in vertical setting. In addition, novels, which are the most =
widely read=20
      kind of book publication, are almost completely in vertical =
setting (some=20
      readers say that they cannot read a novel if it is not in vertical =

      setting.). Hence it can be expected that the importance of =
vertical=20
      setting for Japanese will not change for the time being. =
</P></TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD class=3Dft>
      <P>=E6=B3=A84=EF=BC=89</P></TD>
    <TD>
      <P class=3Dft>There's usually only one direction for all text =
throughout a=20
      book, but there are cases where horizontal composition are =
partially=20
      adopted in vertically composed books, for e.g. running heads =
composed=20
      horizontally (See <SPAN class=3Dfigure_ref>Fig. 1-14</SPAN>). </P>
      <TABLE class=3Dt_sample>
        <TBODY>
        <TR>
          <TD class=3Dft>
            <P>(Example)</P></TD>
          <TD>
            <P class=3Dft>Tables, Captions for Graphics, running heads, =
and folios=20
            composed horizontally in a page with a vertical text=20
        layout.</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE>
      <DIV class=3Dfigure><IMG=20
      alt=3D"Figure 1-14 Example of partial adoption of horizontal =
composition in vertically composed books"=20
      src=3D"http://www.w3.org/TR/jlreq/Images/img1_14.png">=20
      <DIV class=3DfigureTitle><SPAN class=3Dlln>Figure 1-14</SPAN> =
Example of=20
      partial adoption of horizontal composition in vertically composed =
books=20
      =
</DIV></DIV><!--figure--></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE><!--t_note--></DIV><!-=
-div3-->
<DIV class=3Ddiv3>
<H4><A id=3Dsubheading1_3_2 shape=3Drect name=3Dsubheading1_3_2><SPAN=20
class=3Dlln>1.3.2</SPAN> Characteristics of Vertical and Horizontal=20
composition</A></H4>
<P class=3Dbody>The following are major differences between vertical =
composition=20
and horizontal composition.</P>
<OL>
  <LI>
  <P>Arrangement of characters, lines, columns and pages; Direction of =
page=20
  progression.</P>
  <TABLE class=3Dt_note>
    <TBODY>
    <TR>
      <TD class=3Dft>
        <P>(note 1)</P></TD>
      <TD>
        <P class=3Dft>The positioning of characters, lines and =
paragraphs in=20
        vertical and horizontal setting is defined in JIS X 4051, sec.=20
      7.4.4.</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE><!--t_note-->
  <OL>
    <LI>
    <P>Vertical composition (See <SPAN class=3Dfigure_ref>Fig. =
1-15</SPAN> for an=20
    example of vertical text layout with two columns per page) </P>
    <DIV class=3Dfigure><IMG=20
    alt=3D"Figure 1-15 Direction of arrangement for characters and other =
elements in vertical composition."=20
    src=3D"http://www.w3.org/TR/jlreq/Images/img1_15.png">=20
    <DIV class=3DfigureTitle><SPAN class=3Dlln>Figure 1-15</SPAN> =
Direction of=20
    arrangement for characters and other elements in vertical =
composition.=20
    </DIV></DIV><!--figure-->
    <OL>
      <LI>
      <P>Characters are arranged from top to bottom, lines are arranged =
from=20
      right to left.</P>
      <LI>
      <P>Columns are arranged from top to bottom. A book starts with the =
recto=20
      side and progresses from right to left (See <SPAN =
class=3Dfigure_ref>Fig.=20
      1-16</SPAN>). </P>
      <DIV class=3Dfigure><IMG=20
      alt=3D"Figure 1-16 Progression of pages for a book with vertical =
composition"=20
      src=3D"http://www.w3.org/TR/jlreq/Images/img1_16.png">=20
      <DIV class=3DfigureTitle><SPAN class=3Dlln>Figure 1-16</SPAN> =
Progression of=20
      pages for a book with vertical composition=20
    </DIV></DIV><!--figure--></LI></OL>
    <LI>
    <P>Horizontal composition (See <SPAN class=3Dfigure_ref>Fig. =
1-17</SPAN> for=20
    an example of horizontal text layout with two-columns per page) </P>
    <DIV class=3Dfigure><IMG=20
    alt=3D"Figure 1-17 Direction of arrangement for characters and other =
elements in horizontal composition"=20
    src=3D"http://www.w3.org/TR/jlreq/Images/img1_17.png">=20
    <DIV class=3DfigureTitle><SPAN class=3Dlln>Figure 1-17</SPAN> =
Direction of=20
    arrangement for characters and other elements in horizontal =
composition=20
    </DIV></DIV><!--figure-->
    <OL>
      <LI>
      <P>Characters are arranged from left to right, and lines are =
arranged from=20
      top to bottom.</P>
      <LI>
      <P>Columns are arranged from left to right. A book starts with the =
recto=20
      side and progresses from left to right (See <SPAN =
class=3Dfigure_ref>Fig.=20
      1-18</SPAN>). </P>
      <DIV class=3Dfigure><IMG=20
      alt=3D"Figure 1-18 Progression of pages for a book with horizontal =
composition"=20
      src=3D"http://www.w3.org/TR/jlreq/Images/img1_18.png">=20
      <DIV class=3DfigureTitle><SPAN class=3Dlln>Figure 1-18</SPAN> =
Progression of=20
      pages for a book with horizontal composition=20
    </DIV></DIV><!--figure--></LI></OL>
    <LI>
    <P>Orientation of alphanumeric characters in a line</P>
    <OL>
      <LI>
      <P>There are three ways to arrange alphanumerics in vertical=20
      composition.</P>
      <OL>
        <LI>
        <P>Arranging one by one with the same Normal orientation as that =
of=20
        Japanese characters. Usually applied to one letter alphanumeric =
or=20
        capital abbreviations (See <SPAN class=3Dfigure_ref>Fig. =
1-19</SPAN>).=20
</P>
        <DIV class=3Dfigure><IMG=20
        alt=3D"Figure 1-19 Arrangement of alphanumerics in vertical =
composition - 1"=20
        src=3D"http://www.w3.org/TR/jlreq/Images/img1_19.png">=20
        <DIV class=3DfigureTitle><SPAN class=3Dlln>Figure 1-19</SPAN> =
Arrangement of=20
        alphanumerics in vertical composition - 1 =
</DIV></DIV><!--figure-->
        <TABLE class=3Dt_note>
          <TBODY>
          <TR>
            <TD class=3Dft>
              <P>(note 1)</P></TD>
            <TD>
              <P class=3Dft>The alphanumeric characters used for this =
arrangement=20
              have different typographic features than those with =
Propotional=20
              width used for Latin scrip text. They are Monospace =
characters of=20
              Full width design, which have been used since the =
letterpress=20
              era.</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE><!--t_note-->
        <LI>
        <P>Arranging characters after rotating 90 degrees clockwise. =
Usually=20
        applied to English words or sentences (See <SPAN =
class=3Dfigure_ref>Fig.=20
        1-20</SPAN>). </P>
        <DIV class=3Dfigure><IMG=20
        alt=3D"Figure 1-20 Arrangement of alphanumerics in vertical =
composition - 2"=20
        src=3D"http://www.w3.org/TR/jlreq/Images/img1_20.png">=20
        <DIV class=3DfigureTitle><SPAN class=3Dlln>Figure 1-20</SPAN> =
Arrangement of=20
        alphanumerics in vertical composition - 2 =
</DIV></DIV><!--figure-->
        <TABLE class=3Dt_note>
          <TBODY>
          <TR>
            <TD class=3Dft>
              <P>(note 1)</P></TD>
            <TD>
              <P class=3Dft>In <SPAN class=3Dfigure_ref>Figure =
1-20</SPAN>, there is=20
              a gap before and after the imaginary body of =
=E2=80=9Ceditor=E2=80=9D. This gap is=20
              necessary for arrangement of mixed Japanese and Latin =
script text.=20
              Details of its processing will be explained later.=20
          </P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE><!--t_note-->
        <LI>
        <P>Setting horizontally without changing orientation =
(TATECHUYOKO=20
        (horizontal-in-vertical annotation), See <SPAN =
class=3Dfigure_ref>Fig.=20
        1-21</SPAN>). This is usually applied to two-digit numbers (see =
JIS X=20
        4051, sec. 4.8 for the definition.). </P>
        <DIV class=3Dfigure><IMG=20
        alt=3D"Figure 1-21 Arrangement of alphanumerics in vertical =
composition -3 (TATECHUYOKO)"=20
        src=3D"http://www.w3.org/TR/jlreq/Images/img1_21.png">=20
        <DIV class=3DfigureTitle><SPAN class=3Dlln>Figure 1-21</SPAN> =
Arrangement of=20
        alphanumerics in vertical composition -3 (TATECHUYOKO) =
</DIV></DIV><!--figure--></LI></OL>
      <LI>
      <P>There's only one arrangement with normal orientation in =
horizontal=20
      composition.</P></LI></OL>
    <LI>
    <P>Arrangement of Tables and/or Figures with rotating 90 degrees =
clockwise=20
    or anti-clockwise for size considerations (This processing is =
defined in JIS=20
    X 4051, sec. 7.3.).</P>
    <OL>
      <LI>
      <P>In vertical composition, align top of tables/figures to the =
right of=20
      page (See <SPAN class=3Dfigure_ref>Fig. 1-22</SPAN>). </P>
      <DIV class=3Dfigure><IMG=20
      alt=3D"Figure 1-22 Example arrangement of a table rotating 90 =
degrees clockwise in vertical composition"=20
      src=3D"http://www.w3.org/TR/jlreq/Images/img1_22.png">=20
      <DIV class=3DfigureTitle><SPAN class=3Dlln>Figure 1-22</SPAN> =
Example=20
      arrangement of a table rotating 90 degrees clockwise in vertical=20
      composition </DIV></DIV><!--figure-->
      <LI>
      <P>In horizontal composition, align top of tables/figures to the =
left of=20
      page (See <SPAN class=3Dfigure_ref>Fig. 1-23</SPAN>). </P>
      <DIV class=3Dfigure><IMG=20
      alt=3D"Figure 1-23 Example arrangement of a table rotating 90 =
degrees counterclockwise in horizontal composition"=20
      src=3D"http://www.w3.org/TR/jlreq/Images/img1_23.png">=20
      <DIV class=3DfigureTitle><SPAN class=3Dlln>Figure 1-23</SPAN> =
Example=20
      arrangement of a table rotating 90 degrees counterclockwise in =
horizontal=20
      composition </DIV></DIV><!--figure-->
      <TABLE class=3Dt_note>
        <TBODY>
        <TR>
          <TD class=3Dft>
            <P>(note 1)</P></TD>
          <TD>
            <P class=3Dft>The orientation is determined not to prevent =
reading=20
            flow of the=20
  book.</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE><!--t_note--></LI></OL></LI></OL>
  <LI>
  <P>Arrangement of incomplete number of lines on a multi-column format =
page due=20
  to New recto, Page break or other reasons (The processing of new recto =
and=20
  each page is defined in JIS X 4051, sec. 8.1.1.).</P>
  <OL>
    <LI>
    <P>In vertical composition, just finish the line where it ends =
("NARIYUKI").=20
    The number of lines in each column is not uniform. (See <SPAN=20
    class=3Dfigure_ref>Fig. 1-24</SPAN>). </P>
    <DIV class=3Dfigure><IMG=20
    alt=3D"Figure 1-24 How to process incomplete number of lines on a =
multi-column format page. An example in vertical composition."=20
    src=3D"http://www.w3.org/TR/jlreq/Images/img1_24.png">=20
    <DIV class=3DfigureTitle><SPAN class=3Dlln>Figure 1-24</SPAN> How to =
process=20
    incomplete number of lines on a multi-column format page. An example =
in=20
    vertical composition. </DIV></DIV><!--figure-->
    <LI>
    <P>In horizontal composition, re-arrange columns so that each column =
has the=20
    same number of lines on average. In case the number of lines is not=20
    divisible by the number of columns, add the smallest number to make =
it=20
    divisible and re-arrange columns using the quotient as the number of =
lines=20
    so that only the last column shall have the incomplete number of =
lines. (See=20
    <SPAN class=3Dfigure_ref>Fig. 1-25</SPAN>). </P>
    <DIV class=3Dfigure><IMG=20
    alt=3D"Figure 1-25 How to process incomplete number of lines on a =
multi-column format page. An example in horizontal composition."=20
    src=3D"http://www.w3.org/TR/jlreq/Images/img1_25.png">=20
    <DIV class=3DfigureTitle><SPAN class=3Dlln>Figure 1-25</SPAN> How to =
process=20
    incomplete number of lines on a multi-column format page. An example =
in=20
    horizontal composition. </DIV></DIV><!--figure-->
    <TABLE class=3Dt_note>
      <TBODY>
      <TR>
        <TD class=3Dft>
          <P>(note 1)</P></TD>
        <TD>
          <P class=3Dft>Neither Horizontal nor vertical balance of =
column=20
          arrangement would break the stability of vertical page layout =
very=20
          much, while horizontal balance of column arrangement is =
determinant=20
          for horizontal page layout.=20
  =
</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE><!--t_note--></LI></OL></LI></OL></DIV><!--=
div3--></DIV><!--div2-->
<DIV class=3Ddiv2>
<H3><A id=3Dsubheading1_4 shape=3Drect name=3Dsubheading1_4><SPAN =
class=3Dlln>1.4</SPAN>=20
Specification of KIHONHANMEN</A></H3>
<DIV class=3Ddiv3>
<H4><A id=3Dsubheading1_4_1 shape=3Drect name=3Dsubheading1_4_1><SPAN=20
class=3Dlln>1.4.1</SPAN> Procedures to Determine KIHONHANMEN</A></H4>
<P class=3Dbody>In Japanese layout, first the size of KIHONHANMEN is =
defined,=20
using the square imaginary body of characters in solid setting. Taken =
this as a=20
base, the position of KIHONHANMEN with regards to the trim size is =
specified.=20
Now, the following are procedures to determine KIHONHANMEN (See <SPAN=20
class=3Dfigure_ref>Fig. 1-26</SPAN>). </P>
<OL>
  <LI>
  <P>Specifying the dimensions of KIHONHANMEN.</P>
  <OL>
    <LI>
    <P>For a document with a single column per page, specify character =
size,=20
    number of characters per line, number of lines per page, and =
line-gap. </P>
    <LI>
    <P>For a document with multiple columns per page, specify character =
size,=20
    number of characters per line, number of lines per column, line-gap, =
number=20
    of columns, column space. </P>
    <DIV class=3Dfigure><IMG=20
    alt=3D"Figure 1-26-1 Procedures to determine KIHONHANMEN Step 1"=20
    src=3D"http://www.w3.org/TR/jlreq/Images/img1_26_1.png"><BR>
    <DIV class=3DfigureTitle><SPAN class=3Dlln>Figure 1-26-1</SPAN> =
Procedures to=20
    determine KIHONHANMEN Step 1 </DIV></DIV><!--figure--></LI></OL>
  <LI>
  <P>Determining the position of KIHONHANMEN relative to the trim =
size.</P>
  <P>Various alternative methods for specifying the position of =
KIHONHANMEN=20
  relative to the trim size are as follows.</P>
  <OL>
    <LI>Position top and bottom: center. Position left and right: =
center.=20
    <LI>Position top and bottom: specifying the space at the top (for =
horizontal=20
    setting) or space at the bottom (for vertical setting). Left and =
right=20
    position: center.=20
    <LI>Top and bottom position: center. Left and right position: =
specifying the=20
    space of the gutter.=20
    <LI>Position top and bottom: Space at the top (for horizontal =
setting) or=20
    space at the bottom (for vertical setting). Position left and right: =

    specifying the space of the gutter (see <SPAN =
class=3Dfigure_ref>Fig.=20
    1-26-2</SPAN>). </LI></OL>
  <DIV class=3Dfigure><IMG=20
  alt=3D"Figure 1-26-2 Procedures to determine KIHONHANMEN Step 2"=20
  src=3D"http://www.w3.org/TR/jlreq/Images/img1_26_2.png"><BR>
  <DIV class=3DfigureTitle><SPAN class=3Dlln>Figure 1-26-2</SPAN> =
Procedures to=20
  determine KIHONHANMEN Step 2 </DIV></DIV><!--figure-->
  <TABLE class=3Dt_note>
    <TBODY>
    <TR>
      <TD class=3Dft>
        <P>(note 1)</P></TD>
      <TD>
        <P class=3Dft>In most cases KIHONHANMEN is set at the horizontal =
and=20
        vertical center of the trim size, which should be the default=20
        positioning, but depending on the dimensions of KIHONHANMEN =
there may be=20
        a case where the default needs to be changed, for example, by =
moving=20
        KIHONHANMEN up, down, to the left or to the right of the default =

        position. </P></TD></TR>
    <TR>
      <TD class=3Dft>
        <P>(note 2)</P></TD>
      <TD>
        <P class=3Dft>It's technically possible to determine the =
dimensions of=20
        KIHONHANMEN by specifying the trim size and margins of all =
sides, but=20
        this method is not common in the Japanese text layout tradition. =
If this=20
        is the only way an implementation allows, the margins of each =
side need=20
        to be measured in relation to the dimensions of KIHONHANMEN and =
its=20
        position in the trim size.=20
</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE><!--t_note--></LI></OL></DIV><!--div3-->
<DIV class=3Ddiv3>
<H4><A id=3Dsubheading1_4_2 shape=3Drect name=3Dsubheading1_4_2><SPAN=20
class=3Dlln>1.4.2</SPAN> Considerations in Designing =
KIHONHANMEN</A></H4>
<P class=3Dbody>The following are the considerations that should be =
taken into=20
account in designing KIHONHANMEN. (The items a) and b) of this topic are =
not=20
about processing, but rather an explanation about how the design should =
be. The=20
definition of KIHONHANMEN is given in JIS X 4051, sec. 7.4.1.) </P>
<OL>
  <LI>
  <P>Trim size and margins. It would be best if KIHONHANMEN could be =
made=20
  similar to the trim size.</P>
  <LI>
  <P>Character size. Generally 9 points (=E2=89=923.2mm), 8 points =
(=E2=89=922.8mm) at smallest=20
  for books targeted to adults but for special purpose like =
dictionaries. </P>
  <TABLE class=3Dt_note>
    <TBODY>
    <TR>
      <TD class=3Dft>
        <P>(note 1)</P></TD>
      <TD>
        <P class=3Dft>In western typography, 10 points (=E2=89=923.5mm) =
or 12 points=20
        (=E2=89=924.2mm) are commonly used. This is mainly because of a =
difference of=20
        design principles between Japanese characters and Latin =
characters.=20
      </P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE><!--t_note-->
  <LI>
  <P>Line length.</P>
  <OL>
    <LI>
    <P>Line length should be multiples of the character size (See <SPAN=20
    class=3Dfigure_ref>Fig. 1-27</SPAN>). </P>
    <DIV class=3Dfigure><IMG=20
    alt=3D"Figure 1-27 Line length should be multiples of the character =
size"=20
    src=3D"http://www.w3.org/TR/jlreq/Images/img1_27.png">=20
    <DIV class=3DfigureTitle><SPAN class=3Dlln>Figure 1-27</SPAN> Line =
length should=20
    be multiples of the character size </DIV></DIV><!--figure-->
    <TABLE class=3Dt_note>
      <TBODY>
      <TR>
        <TD class=3Dft>
          <P>(note 1)</P></TD>
        <TD>
          <P class=3Dft>There are basically two reasons why line length =
should be=20
          multiples of the character size.</P>
          <OL>
            <LI>
            <P>For Japanese text layout, all line lengths except that of =
the=20
            last line of the Paragraph should be the same in principle.=20
            Furthermore, only the first line of a paragraph is shorter, =
since as=20
            a matter of principle it is indented.</P>
            <LI>
            <P>Japanese characters like KANJI or KANA for printing are =
uniformly=20
            designed in the same square and they are arranged solid (no =
extra=20
            space between adjacent imaginary bodies) in principle.=20
        </P></LI></OL></TD></TR>
      <TR>
        <TD class=3Dft>
          <P>(note 2)</P></TD>
        <TD>
          <P class=3Dft>The best line length (number of ZIZUME or number =
of=20
          characters per line) is around 52 characters at max in =
vertical=20
          composition and 40 characters in horizontal composition. If it =
would=20
          go beyond the recommended length due to the trim size, =
consider=20
          multi-column format and make the line length shorter.=20
      </P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE><!--t_note--></LI></OL>
  <LI>
  <P>Use the same amount of line-gap across the book except special =
cases and=20
  each line should be aligned. With these two conditions, the size of=20
  KIHONHANMEN in the line feed direction is specified with number of =
lines and=20
  line-gap (or line height, GYO-OKURI). </P>
  <TABLE class=3Dt_note>
    <TBODY>
    <TR>
      <TD class=3Dft>
        <P>(note 1)</P></TD>
      <TD>
        <P class=3Dft>In Japanese layout, there are cases that RUBY, =
KENTEN,=20
        BOSEN, under lines etc. are inserted between lines. The =
inter-line=20
        spacing is not changed and kept constant for these cases as well =
(see=20
        <SPAN class=3Dfigure_ref>Fig. A1-5</SPAN>). It is also possible =
to insert=20
        references to notes between lines within the main text. This =
case is=20
        handled in the same manner. Further explanation about the =
placement of=20
        RUBY will be given in sec. 2. </P>
        <DIV class=3Dfigure><IMG=20
        alt=3D"Figure A1-5 Inserting RUBY or other items between lines"=20
        src=3D"http://www.w3.org/TR/jlreq/Images/img_ad1_5.png">=20
        <DIV class=3DfigureTitle>Figure A1-5 Inserting RUBY or other =
items between=20
        lines</DIV></DIV><!--figure--></TD></TR>
    <TR>
      <TD class=3Dft>
        <P>(note 2)</P></TD>
      <TD>
        <P class=3Dft>WARICHU juts out of the width of the line feed =
direction=20
        (the character size designed via KIHONHANMEN). Also for these =
cases, the=20
        inter-line spacing is defined for the parts without WARICHU, and =
the=20
        passages with WARICHU are made narrower (see <SPAN =
class=3Dfigure_ref>Fig.=20
        A1-18</SPAN>). Hence, for WARICHU, inter-line spacing is larger =
to some=20
        extend. The same is true for TATECHUYOKO or sub- and =
superscript.=20
        Further explanations of the placement of WARICHU and other items =
is=20
        provided in sec. 2. </P>
        <DIV class=3Dfigure><IMG=20
        alt=3D"Figure A1-18 Example of inter-line processing with =
WARICHU between lines"=20
        src=3D"http://www.w3.org/TR/jlreq/Images/img_ad1_18.png">=20
        <DIV class=3DfigureTitle>Figure A1-18 Example of inter-line =
processing=20
        with WARICHU between lines</DIV></DIV><!--figure--></TD></TR>
    <TR>
      <TD class=3Dft>
        <P>(note 3)</P></TD>
      <TD>
        <P class=3Dft>It is common that line-gap for KIHONHANMEN is set =
a value=20
        between 1/2 em space and full width (em) of the character size =
in=20
        KIHONHANMEN. 1/2 em space can be chosen in case the number of =
characters=20
        per line is small, but full width (em) or close to it should be=20
        appropriate when it is larger than 35 characters. </P></TD></TR>
    <TR>
      <TD class=3Dft>
        <P>(note 4)</P></TD>
      <TD>
        <P class=3Dft>Unless RUBY or other design elements are placed in =
the space=20
        between lines for books like classics with many annotations, =
there's no=20
        need to make line-gap larger than full width, which would not =
improve=20
        legibility. </P></TD></TR>
    <TR>
      <TD class=3Dft>
        <P>(note 5)</P></TD>
      <TD>
        <P class=3Dft>It is said that the standard line-gap in western =
typography=20
        is 1/3 em space, which is smaller than that in Japanese text =
layout.=20
        This difference again comes from the design difference between =
Latin=20
        characters and Japanese characters. =
</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE><!--t_note--></LI></OL></DIV><!--div3--></D=
IV><!--div2-->
<DIV class=3Ddiv2>
<H3><A id=3Dsubheading1_5 shape=3Drect name=3Dsubheading1_5>1.5 Pagewise =
Arrangements=20
of KIHONHANMEN Elements</A></H3>
<DIV class=3Ddiv3>
<H3><A id=3Dsubheading1_5_1 shape=3Drect name=3Dsubheading1_5_1>1.5.1 =
Examples of=20
Jutting out of KIHONHANMEN</A></H3>
<P>If at all possible, the various elements of a page should be inside =
the=20
HANMEN size. This is which is determined by KIHONHANMEN. However, there =
are=20
exceptions like the following ones. </P>
<OL>
  <LI>
  <P>If there is RUBY, BOSEN, KENTEN etc. at the right side (for =
vertical=20
  setting) or upper side (for horizontal setting) of the HANMEN or the =
first=20
  paragraph of a page, the added item is put outside the HANMEN or the =
area of=20
  the paragraph (see <SPAN class=3Dfigure_ref>Fig. A1-6</SPAN>). In =
cases where=20
  RUBY, under lines etc. are put on the left (in vertical setting) or =
bottom=20
  (horizontal composition), the item is in contact with the HANMEN or =
the line=20
  at the end of the paragraph. Like for the handling of exceptions =
mentioned=20
  below, the purpose here is to preserve the line positions which are =
provided=20
  via KIHONHANMEN. It is also possible to insert references to notes =
between=20
  lines within the main text. This case is handled in the same manner. =
</P>
  <DIV class=3Dfigure><IMG=20
  alt=3D"Figure A1-6 Example of ruby annotation placed outside of =
KIHONHANMEN"=20
  src=3D"http://www.w3.org/TR/jlreq/Images/img_ad1_6.png">=20
  <DIV class=3DfigureTitle>Figure A1-6 Example of ruby annotation placed =
outside=20
  of KIHONHANMEN</DIV></DIV><!--figure-->
  <LI>
  <P>In cases where there are elements in HANMEN, the first column or =
the last=20
  line (e.g. of a paragraph) which jut out of the width of the line feed =

  direction given by KIHONHANMEN (the character size specified via =
KIHONHANMEN),=20
  the parts of the item which just out of the line width of the line =
feed=20
  direction given by KIHONHANMEN, are put jutting out of the HANMEN area =
or=20
  outer side of the column (The processing of this item and item a) is =
defined=20
  in JIS X 4051, sec. 12.1.1.). For example this is the case when the =
width of a=20
  sequence of characters which are set to TATECHUYOKO is larger than the =
width=20
  of characters set for KIHONHANMEN. In addition, WARICHU or sub- and=20
  superscript are handled the same. </P>
  <LI>
  <P>The processing of so-called hanging punctuation is only necessary =
for KUTEN=20
  (=E3=80=82) and TOUTEN (=E3=80=81) which need line head wrap: The =
character is placed so that=20
  it touches the HANMEN of the line end or the outside area of the =
column (see=20
  <SPAN class=3Dfigure_ref>Fig. A1-7</SPAN>). Furthermore, hanging =
punctuation is=20
  not defined in JIS X 4051, but there is an explanation in sec. 8.1, =
c). </P>
  <DIV class=3Dfigure><IMG=20
  alt=3D"Figure A1-7 Example of ideographic comma and ideographic full =
stop hanging below off of the KIHONHANMEN"=20
  src=3D"http://www.w3.org/TR/jlreq/Images/img_ad1_7.png">=20
  <DIV class=3DfigureTitle>Figure A1-7 Example of ideographic comma and=20
  ideographic full stop placed below the =
KIHONHANMEN</DIV></DIV><!--figure-->
  <TABLE class=3Dt_note>
    <TBODY>
    <TR>
      <TD class=3Dft>
        <P>(note 1)</P></TD>
      <TD>
        <P class=3Dft>Hanging punctuation is a method to reduce line =
adjustment=20
        processing, which relies on inter-character =
spacing.</P></TD></TR>
    <TR>
      <TD class=3Dft>
        <P>(note 2)</P></TD>
      <TD>
        <P class=3Dft>There are a lot of books which apply hanging=20
      punctuation.</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE><!--t_note-->
  <LI>
  <P>Illustrations and tables are normally placed inside the area which =
is=20
  defined via KIHONHANMEN. However, depending on the illustration or =
table,=20
  there are also cases in which they jut outside the area of =
KIHONHANMEN. </P>
  <OL>
    <LI>
    <P>Cases in which it is necessary to make the illustration or table =
larger=20
    than KIHONHANMEN.</P>
    <LI>
    <P>To achieve a visual effect, the illustration or table juts =
outside of=20
    KIHONHANMEN. Especially the "bleeds" method of using the complete =
paper area=20
    is not used often books, but in magazines (see <SPAN =
class=3Dfigure_ref>Fig.=20
    A1-8</SPAN>). </P>
    <DIV class=3Dfigure><IMG alt=3D"Figure A1-8 Example of bleeds"=20
    src=3D"http://www.w3.org/TR/jlreq/Images/img_ad1_8.png">=20
    <DIV class=3DfigureTitle>Figure A1-8 Example of =
bleeds</DIV></DIV><!--figure--></LI></OL>
  <LI>
  <P>In addition, the method of placing the captions of figures outside =
the=20
  column area or between columns is used in journals (Some people regard =
this as=20
  bad style.). </P></LI></OL></DIV><!--div3-->
<DIV class=3Ddiv3>
<H3><A id=3Dsubheading1_5_2 shape=3Drect name=3Dsubheading1_5_2>1.5.2 =
Line Positioning=20
relying on KIHONHANMEN Design</A></H3>
<P>In principle, pagewise positioning of lines relies on the line =
positions=20
given via KIHONHANMEN. This is also true for RUBY or KENTEN like in =
<SPAN=20
class=3Dfigure_ref>Figure A1-5</SPAN>, and also with characters as shown =
in <SPAN=20
class=3Dfigure_ref>Figure A1-9</SPAN>. These characters within a line =
are smaller=20
than the characters size provided by KIHONHANMEN. Nevertheless, the line =

positions given by KIHONHANMEN is taken as a base, and the subsequent =
lines also=20
use these positions. </P>
<DIV class=3Dfigure><IMG=20
alt=3D"Figure A1-9 Positioning of lines with a mix of a smaller size of =
text"=20
src=3D"http://www.w3.org/TR/jlreq/Images/img_ad1_9.png">=20
<DIV class=3DfigureTitle>Figure A1-9 Positioning of lines with a mix of =
a smaller=20
size of text</DIV></DIV><!--figure-->
<TABLE class=3Dt_note>
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD class=3Dft>
      <P>(note 1)</P></TD>
    <TD>
      <P class=3Dft>The characters within brackets are made smaller =
since the text=20
      is an additional explanation. There are the following three =
methods of=20
      handling such cases. The method c) of making only characters in =
restricted=20
      places smaller is the most commonly used one. </P>
      <OL>
        <LI>
        <P>Making all characters within brackets smaller (as it is shown =
in=20
        <SPAN class=3Dfigure_ref>Figure A1-9</SPAN>). </P>
        <LI>
        <P>Making all characters within brackets the same size as the =
character=20
        size given via KIHONHANMEN.</P>
        <LI>
        <P>Making the characters only in restricted places smaller, for =
example=20
        for =
references.</P></LI></OL></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE><!--t_note-->
<P>There are the following exceptions of line position handling.</P>
<OL>
  <LI>
  <P>In horizontal composition, assuming that there is no text to the =
left or=20
  right of an illustration or table, it can happen that when inserting =
more than=20
  one illustration or table, they slip of the lines given via =
KIHONHANMEN (see=20
  <SPAN class=3Dfigure_ref>Fig. A1-10</SPAN>). But the illustration or =
table may=20
  also rely on the lines given via KIHONHANMEN (see <SPAN =
class=3Dfigure_ref>Fig.=20
  A1-11</SPAN>). The former method is used to achieve equal space before =
and=20
  after illustrations or tables, if at all possible (This method is =
often used=20
  in books.). This processing method is defined in JIS X 4051, sec. =
10.3.2., d).=20
  </P>
  <DIV class=3Dfigure><IMG=20
  alt=3D"Figure A1-10 Positioning of lines with multiple illustrations - =
1"=20
  src=3D"http://www.w3.org/TR/jlreq/Images/img_ad1_10.png">=20
  <DIV class=3DfigureTitle>Figure A1-10 Positioning of lines with =
multiple=20
  illustrations - 1</DIV></DIV><!--figure-->
  <DIV class=3Dfigure><IMG=20
  alt=3D"Figure A1-11 Positioning of lines with multiple illustrations - =
2"=20
  src=3D"http://www.w3.org/TR/jlreq/Images/img_ad1_11.png">=20
  <DIV class=3DfigureTitle>Figure A1-11 Positioning of lines with =
multiple=20
  illustrations - 2</DIV></DIV><!--figure-->
  <LI>
  <P>Notes which are inserted between paragraphs or at the bottom of the =
page=20
  (in horizontal composition) are smaller than the character size given =
via=20
  KIHONHANMEN. As a result, the line distance becomes smaller, and the =
line=20
  positions are not identical to the lines given via KIHONHANMEN. As an =
example,=20
  <SPAN class=3Dfigure_ref>Figure A1-12</SPAN> shows the position of an =
endnote=20
  between paragraphs in vertical composition. The processing of endnotes =
is=20
  defined in JIS X 4051, sec. 9.3, and the processing of footnotes in =
sec. 9.4.=20
  </P>
  <DIV class=3Dfigure><IMG=20
  alt=3D"Figure A1-12 Positioning of an endnote in vertical composition" =

  src=3D"http://www.w3.org/TR/jlreq/Images/img_ad1_12.png">=20
  <DIV class=3DfigureTitle>Figure A1-12 Positioning of an endnote in =
vertical=20
  composition</DIV></DIV><!--figure-->
  <LI>
  <P>As mentioned above, it may happen that the position of headings is =
not=20
  identical with the lines given via KIHONHANMEN. Nevertheless, the area =
of the=20
  line feed direction uses the lines given via KIHONHANMEN as a basis =
(see <SPAN=20
  class=3Dfigure_ref>Fig. A1-1</SPAN>). </P></LI></OL></DIV><!--div3-->
<DIV class=3Ddiv3>
<H3><A id=3Dsubheading1_5_3 shape=3Drect name=3Dsubheading1_5_3>1.5.3 =
Character=20
Positioning relying on KIHONHANMEN Design</A></H3>
<P>In principle, the characters in each line follow the solid setting =
positions=20
of characters, which are given via KIHONHANMEN. However, as already =
shown in=20
some of the previous figures, there are examples in which the character=20
positions do not follow the positions given via KIHONHANMEN. Such cases =
are=20
rather common, and here we will show some prototypical examples (details =
will be=20
given in sec. 2). </P>
<TABLE class=3Dt_note>
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD class=3Dft>
      <P>(note 1)</P></TD>
    <TD>
      <P class=3Dft>In cases when there are places which differ from the =
character=20
      size of solid setting given via KIHONHANMEN, it may happen that =
line=20
      lengths are not identical; it will be necessary to unify the =
lengths of=20
      lines, with the exception of the last line of a paragraph. This =
processing=20
      method is explained in sec. 2.8. "Characters Not Ending Line".=20
  </P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE><!--t_note-->
<OL>
  <LI>
  <P>It may happen that in a part of a line, characters are inserted =
which are=20
  smaller than 9 points (see <SPAN class=3Dfigure_ref>Fig. A1-9</SPAN>). =
This is a=20
  size provided via KIHONHANMEN. In such cases, the parts with 9 points =
given=20
  via KIHONHANMEN use solid setting with an imaginary body of 9 points. =
In=20
  addition, the smaller parts with 8 points use solid setting with an =
imaginary=20
  body of 8 points. </P>
  <LI>
  <P>In cases with proportional, Latin script text (see <SPAN=20
  class=3Dfigure_ref>Fig. 1-20</SPAN>) rotated clockwise 90 degrees, the =

  proportional, Latin characters are placed in accordance with their =
width.=20
  Hence, they do not follow the character positions given via =
KIHONHANMEN (see=20
  <SPAN class=3Dfigure_ref>Fig. A1-13</SPAN>). The Japanese characters =
following=20
  the Latin characters slip of as well. </P>
  <DIV class=3Dfigure><IMG=20
  alt=3D"Figure A1-13 Positioning of a mix of Latin and Japanese =
characters in a line"=20
  src=3D"http://www.w3.org/TR/jlreq/Images/img_ad1_13.png">=20
  <DIV class=3DfigureTitle>Figure A1-13 Positioning of a mix of Latin =
and Japanese=20
  characters in a line</DIV></DIV><!--figure-->
  <LI>
  <P>There are several methods for positioning brackets at the head of =
line feed=20
  lines or lines after the first line of a paragraph (details are =
explained in=20
  sec. 2.1.5 "Positioning of Brackets at Line Head".). In cases where =
the=20
  indentation of line feed lines is full width, or if the TENTSUKI =
position is=20
  used for the bracket (that is, there is no space at the line head), =
the second=20
  character will be in a position which is not given via KIHONHANMEN =
(see <SPAN=20
  class=3Dfigure_ref>Fig. A1-14</SPAN>). However, since adaptation =
processing for=20
  the unification of line lengths is applied, the characters at the end =
of the=20
  line are at positions which are in accordance with the positions given =
via=20
  KIHONHANMEN. </P>
  <DIV class=3Dfigure><IMG=20
  alt=3D"Figure A1-14 Example of positioning of characters off to the =
grid due to the brackets at the line head"=20
  src=3D"http://www.w3.org/TR/jlreq/Images/img_ad1_14.png">=20
  <DIV class=3DfigureTitle>Figure A1-14 Example of positioning of =
characters off=20
  to the grid due to the brackets at the line =
head</DIV></DIV><!--figure-->
  <LI>
  <P>Sec. 2 explains that punctuation marks and brackets are half width. =
If=20
  these punctuation marks and brackets are in continuation with Kanji or =
Kana=20
  characters, in principle there is a 1/2 em space before or after the=20
  punctuation mark or brackets, so that these are made in effect a full =
width=20
  size. However, if they are in continuation with other punctuation =
marks or=20
  brackets, the 1/2 em space is not used. In such cases, the character =
positions=20
  are different than the positions given via KIHONHANMEN (see <SPAN=20
  class=3Dfigure_ref>Fig. A1-15</SPAN>). The purpose is to improve the =
visual=20
  appearance. </P>
  <DIV class=3Dfigure><IMG=20
  alt=3D"Figure A1-15 Example of lines with consecutive punctuation =
marks"=20
  src=3D"http://www.w3.org/TR/jlreq/Images/img_ad1_15.png">=20
  <DIV class=3DfigureTitle>Figure A1-15 Example of lines with =
consecutive=20
  punctuation marks</DIV></DIV><!--figure-->
  <LI>
  <P>Sec. 2 explains the principle that closing brackets and punctuation =
marks=20
  must not be placed at the line head (so-called line head wrap). If =
these=20
  characters appear at the line head, some kind of adaptation processing =
becomes=20
  necessary. As a result of such adaptation processing, it may happen =
that=20
  characters are placed at positions which are different than the =
positions=20
  given via KIHONHANMEN. </P>
  <DIV class=3Dfigure><IMG=20
  alt=3D"Figure A1-16 Example of line adjustment to avoid those =
characters which should not start a line, such as closing brackets"=20
  src=3D"http://www.w3.org/TR/jlreq/Images/img_ad1_16.png">=20
  <DIV class=3DfigureTitle>Figure A1-16 Example of line adjustment to =
avoid those=20
  characters which should not start a line, such as closing =
brackets</DIV></DIV><!--figure--></LI></OL></DIV><!--div3--></DIV><!--div=
2-->
<DIV class=3Ddiv2>
<H3><A id=3Dsubheading1_6 shape=3Drect name=3Dsubheading1_6><SPAN =
class=3Dlln>1.6</SPAN>=20
Running Heads and Folios</A></H3>
<DIV class=3Ddiv3>
<H4><A id=3Dsubheading1_6_1 shape=3Drect name=3Dsubheading1_6_1><SPAN=20
class=3Dlln>1.6.1</SPAN> Positioning of Running Heads and =
Folios</A></H4>
<P class=3Dbody>Typical positioning of running heads and folios in =
vertical=20
composition is as shown in <SPAN class=3Dfigure_ref>Fig. 1-28</SPAN>. =
</P>
<DIV class=3Dfigure><IMG=20
alt=3D"Figure 1-28 Typical positioning of running heads and folios in =
vertical composition"=20
src=3D"http://www.w3.org/TR/jlreq/Images/img1_28.png">=20
<DIV class=3DfigureTitle><SPAN class=3Dlln>Figure 1-28</SPAN> Typical =
positioning of=20
running heads and folios in vertical composition =
</DIV></DIV><!--figure-->
<P class=3Dbody>Typical positioning of running heads and folios in =
horizontal=20
composition is as shown in <SPAN class=3Dfigure_ref>Fig. 1-29</SPAN>. =
</P>
<DIV class=3Dfigure><IMG=20
alt=3D"Figure 1-29 Typical positioning of running heads and folios in =
horizontal composition"=20
src=3D"http://www.w3.org/TR/jlreq/Images/img1_29.png">=20
<DIV class=3DfigureTitle><SPAN class=3Dlln>Figure 1-29</SPAN> Typical =
positioning of=20
running heads and folios in horizontal composition =
</DIV></DIV><!--figure-->
<P class=3Dbody>In principle, positions of running heads and folios =
should be=20
specified with relative positions to KIHONHANMEN, not with the absolute=20
coordinates in the trim size (Position of running heads are defined in =
JIS X=20
4051, sec. 7.6.4. Positions of folios are defined in JIS X 4051, sec. =
7.5.4.).=20
</P>
<TABLE class=3Dt_sample>
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD class=3Dft>
      <P>(Example)</P></TD>
    <TD>
      <P>Positioning a running head above the top left corner ( to Head =
and=20
      Fore-edge) of KIHONHANMEN in vertical composition (See <SPAN=20
      class=3Dfigure_ref>Fig. 1-30</SPAN>) </P>
      <P>9 points above KIHONHANMEN (vertical space)</P>
      <P>9 points from the left edge of KIHONHANMEN (horizontal=20
  space)</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE>
<DIV class=3Dfigure><IMG=20
alt=3D"Figure 1-30 Positioning of a running head (vertical composition)" =

src=3D"http://www.w3.org/TR/jlreq/Images/img1_30.png">=20
<DIV class=3DfigureTitle><SPAN class=3Dlln>Figure 1-30</SPAN> =
Positioning of a=20
running head (vertical composition) </DIV></DIV><!--figure-->
<P class=3Dbody>The following are those that should be taken into =
account in=20
positioning running heads and folios with reference to KIHONHANMEN.</P>
<OL>
  <LI>
  <P>When positioning running heads and folios horizontally with =
reference to=20
  KIHONHANMEN in vertical composition, the amount of vertical space is =
full=20
  width of character size in KIHONHANMEN. If KIHONHANMEN is horizontally =
set,=20
  make more vertical space than the character size in KIHONHANMEN. </P>
  <LI>
  <P>Regardless of direction of text in KIHONHANMEN, running heads and =
folios in=20
  horizontal composition on the left page should be aligned either at =
the left=20
  edge of KIHONHANMEN or at the full width horizontal space off to the =
right=20
  from the left edge. On the right page, the tail of the running heads =
or folios=20
  be aligned either at the right edge of KIHONHANMEN or at the full =
width space=20
  off from the right edge. </P>
  <LI>
  <P>When arranging a running head and a folio together horizontally, =
space=20
  between the running head and the folio should be double or one and a =
half time=20
  of the character size for the running head. </P>
  <LI>
  <P>When positioning running heads and folios vertically to the edge =
with=20
  reference to KIHONHANMEN in vertical composition (See the bottom left =
spread=20
  in <SPAN class=3Dfigure_ref>Fig. 1-28</SPAN> for example) the minimum =
horizontal=20
  space should be the same amount as that of the line-gap of =
KIHONHANMEN. The=20
  start of the running head should be placed with a space as large as =
around=20
  four times of the character size of KIHONHANMEN below off the head, =
and with a=20
  space as large as around the five times above off the foot. </P>
  <TABLE class=3Dt_note>
    <TBODY>
    <TR>
      <TD class=3Dft>
        <P>(note 1)</P></TD>
      <TD>
        <P class=3Dft>In general, Ideographic numerals are used for =
vertically set=20
        folios, and Arabic numerals for horizontal pagination. When =
giving=20
        Different pagination on the Front matter, small Roman Numerals =
are used=20
        for the horizontal=20
pagination.</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE><!--t_note--></LI></OL></DIV><!-=
-div3-->
<DIV class=3Ddiv3>
<H4><A id=3Dsubheading1_6_2 shape=3Drect name=3Dsubheading1_6_2><SPAN=20
class=3Dlln>1.6.2</SPAN> Principles of Arrangement of Running Heads and=20
Folios</A></H4>
<P class=3Dbody>Positioning of all running heads and folios in the same =
book=20
should be consistent.</P>
<TABLE class=3Dt_note>
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD class=3Dft>
      <P>(note 1)</P></TD>
    <TD>
      <P class=3Dft>Even on a page with text area smaller than =
KIHONHANMEN in size=20
      such as for Table of contents or Index, positioning of running =
head and=20
      folio shall be the same. In other words, the positioning of =
running heads=20
      and folios with reference to those areas smaller than KIHONHANMEN =
in size=20
      shall be changed. The following <SPAN class=3Dfigure_ref>Figure =
A1-17</SPAN>=20
      demonstrates the relations of the HANMEN for table of contents and =
running=20
      heads or folios. As shown in <SPAN class=3Dfigure_ref>Figure =
A1-3</SPAN>,=20
      this HANMEN is smaller than KIHONHANMEN. <SPAN =
class=3Dfigure_ref>Figure=20
      A1-31</SPAN> demonstrates the relations of positions of running =
heads and=20
      folios for the HANMEN of indices. These HANMEN are not only 4 =
point=20
      smaller at the left and right, but also 5 point smaller at the top =
and=20
      bottom. </P>
      <DIV class=3Dfigure><IMG=20
      alt=3D"Figure A1-17 Positioning of running heads and folios on TOC =
pages on which HANMEN is smaller than KIHONHANMEN in size"=20
      src=3D"http://www.w3.org/TR/jlreq/Images/img_ad1_17.png">=20
      <DIV class=3DfigureTitle><SPAN>Figure A1-17</SPAN> Positioning of =
running=20
      heads and folios on TOC pages on which HANMEN is smaller than =
KIHONHANMEN=20
      in size. </DIV></DIV><!--figure-->
      <DIV class=3Dfigure><IMG=20
      alt=3D"Figure 1-31 Positioning of running heads and folios on =
index pages on which HANMEN is smaller than KIHONHANMEN in size"=20
      src=3D"http://www.w3.org/TR/jlreq/Images/img1_31.png">=20
      <DIV class=3DfigureTitle><SPAN>Figure 1-31</SPAN> Positioning of =
running=20
      heads and folios on index pages on which HANMEN is smaller than=20
      KIHONHANMEN in size. =
</DIV></DIV><!--figure--></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE><!--t_note-->
<P class=3Dbody>Because the start of page shall be on the recto side, =
the=20
right-hand page of a Spread in vertical composition is always even page =
and the=20
left-hand page is always odd page (See <SPAN class=3Dfigure_ref>Fig. =
1-32</SPAN>).=20
Likewise, the left-hand page of a spread in horizontal composition is =
always=20
even page and the right-hand page is always odd page (See <SPAN=20
class=3Dfigure_ref>Fig. 1-33</SPAN>). </P>
<DIV class=3Dfigure><IMG=20
alt=3D"Figure 1-32 Folios on a spread in vertical composition"=20
src=3D"http://www.w3.org/TR/jlreq/Images/img1_32.png">=20
<DIV class=3DfigureTitle><SPAN class=3Dlln>Figure 1-32</SPAN> Folios on =
a spread in=20
vertical composition </DIV></DIV><!--figure-->
<DIV class=3Dfigure><IMG=20
alt=3D"Figure 1-33 Folios on a spread in horizontal composition"=20
src=3D"http://www.w3.org/TR/jlreq/Images/img1_33.png">=20
<DIV class=3DfigureTitle><SPAN class=3Dlln>Figure 1-33</SPAN> Folios on =
a spread in=20
horizontal composition </DIV></DIV><!--figure--></DIV><!--div3-->
<DIV class=3Ddiv3>
<H3><A id=3Dsubheading1_6_3 shape=3Drect name=3Dsubheading1_6_3><SPAN=20
class=3Dlln>1.6.3</SPAN> Types of Arrangement of Running Heads and =
Folios</A></H3>
<P class=3Dbody>There are two methods to arrange running heads =
(Arrangement of=20
running heads is defined in JIS X 4051, sec. 7.6.2. Folios are defined =
in sec.=20
7.5.2.).</P>
<UL>
  <LI>
  <P>Double running head scheme: Print running heads on both Even pages =
and Odd=20
  pages (See <SPAN class=3Dfigure_ref>Fig. 1-34</SPAN>). </P>
  <LI>
  <P>Single running head scheme: Print running heads only on odd pages =
(See=20
  <SPAN class=3Dfigure_ref>Fig. 1-35</SPAN>). </P></LI></UL>
<DIV class=3Dfigure><IMG alt=3D"Figure 1-34 Double running head scheme"=20
src=3D"http://www.w3.org/TR/jlreq/Images/img1_34.png">=20
<DIV class=3DfigureTitle><SPAN class=3Dlln>Figure 1-34</SPAN> Double =
running head=20
scheme </DIV></DIV><!--figure-->
<DIV class=3Dfigure><IMG alt=3D"Figure 1-35 Single running head scheme"=20
src=3D"http://www.w3.org/TR/jlreq/Images/img1_35.png">=20
<DIV class=3DfigureTitle><SPAN class=3Dlln>Figure 1-35</SPAN> Single =
running head=20
scheme </DIV></DIV><!--figure-->
<TABLE class=3Dt_note>
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD class=3Dft>
      <P>(note 1)</P></TD>
    <TD>
      <P class=3Dft>In general, there will be only one running head per =
page.=20
      However there are some cases like dictionaries where multiple =
running=20
      heads are printed to show contents. </P></TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD class=3Dft>
      <P>(note 2)</P></TD>
    <TD>
      <P class=3Dft>In general, there will be only one folio per page. =
However=20
      there are some cases where multiple folios are printed as in the =
following=20
      examples: </P>
      <OL>
        <LI>
        <P>When placing horizontally set Index and/or Bibliography at =
the end of=20
        a volume in vertical composition, Reversal Pagination and =
Continuous=20
        pagination will be printed.</P>
        <LI>
        <P>For Multivolume Work, serial Folios throughout the work and =
folios=20
        per volume will be =
printed.</P></LI></OL></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE><!--t_note-->
<OL>
  <LI>
  <P>In double running head scheme, main Headings with high-level title =
of=20
  contents or the title of book are printed on the even pages, and on =
odd pages=20
  the heading subordinate to the main title or the heading one level =
below the=20
  heading from the even page is is printed. On pages with no subheadings =
like=20
  pages for a table of contents, the same running heads are printed on =
both even=20
  and odd pages. </P>
  <TABLE class=3Dt_note>
    <TBODY>
    <TR>
      <TD class=3Dft>
        <P>(note 1)</P></TD>
      <TD>
        <P class=3Dft>It depends on the content of a book what is =
printed in=20
        running heads. The main purpose of running heads is to help =
readers to=20
        find what is written on each page, or to understand the content =
of the=20
        current page. For this purpose, it does not make much sense to =
print the=20
        name of the book within the running head. The most common =
approach for=20
        headings with three levels is to print the largest heading and =
the=20
        heading on the next level. =
</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE><!--t_note-->
  <LI>
  <P>In single running head scheme, either of the above is selected and=20
  printed.</P>
  <LI>
  <P>In principle, the contents of running heads will be the same as =
those of=20
  headings with the following differences;</P>
  <OL>
    <LI>
    <P>Numbers and words in alphanumeric characters in vertically set =
headings=20
    should be changed to horizontal notation for horizontally set =
running heads.=20
    </P>
    <LI>
    <P>If headings are too long, make them shorter by paraphrasing them =
in fewer=20
    characters. Running heads with too many characters will not give a =
good=20
    appearance. </P>
    <LI>
    <P>For certain publications like a collection of monographs, the =
name of=20
    authors may be added at the end of headings in =
Parenthesis.</P></LI></OL>
  <LI>
  <P>In principle, text direction of running heads and folios should be =
the same=20
  as that of KIHONHANMEN. In case of vertical composition, however, it =
is more=20
  common to set running heads and folios horizontally. </P>
  <LI>
  <P>In principle, running heads are printed on all odd pages in single =
running=20
  head scheme, and on all even and odd pages in double running head =
scheme.=20
  However, for the sake of appearance, they may be omitted on pages like =
the=20
  following. </P>
  <OL>
    <LI>
    <P>Pages on which running heads should be hidden</P>
    <OL>
      <LI>
      <P>Divisional title and Simplified divisional title</P>
      <LI>
      <P>A page where a running head overlaps with other elements like=20
      figures</P>
      <LI>
      <P>A Blank page</P></LI></OL>
    <LI>
    <P>Pages on which running heads may be hidden</P>
    <OL>
      <LI>
      <P>A page where a figure or a table is positioned adjacent to the =
running=20
      head</P>
      <LI>
      <P>A page with a heading right after new recto or new=20
  page</P></LI></OL></LI></OL>
  <LI>
  <P>In principle, folios are printed on all pages. However, for the =
sake of=20
  appearance, they may be omitted on pages with the following =
conditions. </P>
  <OL>
    <LI>
    <P>Pages on which folios should be hidden</P>
    <OL>
      <LI>
      <P>A page on which a figure or a table is positioned adjacent to =
the=20
      folio</P>
      <LI>
      <P>A blank page</P></LI></OL>
    <LI>
    <P>Pages on which folios may be hidden</P>
    <OL>
      <LI>
      <P>Divisional title and simplified divisional title</P>
      <LI>
      <P>A page in horizontal composition with a folio placed on the =
margin to=20
      the head and with a heading right after new recto or new page (In =
this=20
      case, there is also the method of moving the folios to the foot=20
      center.).</P></LI></OL></LI></OL>
  <TABLE class=3Dt_note>
    <TBODY>
    <TR>
      <TD class=3Dft>
        <P>(note 1)</P></TD>
      <TD>
        <P class=3Dft>Cases in which there are pages which are not =
counted are for=20
        example as follows.</P>
        <OL>
          <LI>
          <P>if the main title page is the enclosure;</P>
          <LI>
          <P>if a frontispiece is inserted in the opening page of a =
book; or</P>
          <LI>
          <P>if an illustration of the enclosure or a divisional title =
is=20
          inserted in the main =
text.</P></LI></OL></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE><!--t_note-->
  <LI>
  <P>There are two types of folios. "Serial pagination" means that =
folios are=20
  continued through one complete book. "Different pagination" means that =
folios=20
  are started from "1" separatley at the front matter and back matter. =
Also, for=20
  example in manuals, there is also the method of starting from folio =
"1" for=20
  each chapter (In these cases, it is common that before the folio, the =
name of=20
  the chapter is added as a prefix.). </P>
  <TABLE class=3Dt_note>
    <TBODY>
    <TR>
      <TD class=3Dft>
        <P>(note 1)</P></TD>
      <TD>
        <P class=3Dft>If the front matter and the main text have =
different folios,=20
        each is starting with folio "1". In this case, it is common to =
use Roman=20
        numerals for the front matter, in order to distinguish it from =
the main=20
        text. </P></TD></TR>
    <TR>
      <TD class=3Dft>
        <P>(note 2)</P></TD>
      <TD>
        <P class=3Dft>For books in vertical setting with indices in =
horizontal=20
        setting, the following methods are available.</P>
        <OL>
          <LI>
          <P>So-called reversal pagination. The index in horizontal =
setting is=20
          starting at the end of the book, and folios are added starting =
with=20
          "1" in reverse order (viewed from the flow of the book). </P>
          <LI>
          <P>So-called serial pagination. The index in horizontal =
setting is=20
          starting at the end of the book, and folios are added starting =
with=20
          "1" in the same order as the flow of the book. </P>
          <LI>
          <P>Usage of both reversal and serial pagination. In these =
cases, the=20
          folios of serial pagination are in the same position as the =
folios of=20
          the main text, and folios in reversal pagination are in a =
different=20
          position (for example, if serial pagination is at the foot, =
reversal=20
          pagination is at the head). Often methods to distinct the =
different=20
          paginations are applied, like using Arabic numbers like for =
the main=20
          text, but adding brackets before and after.=20
  =
</P></LI></OL></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE><!--t_note--></LI></OL></DIV><!--=
div3--></DIV><!--div2--></DIV>
